These trends to present themselves when major financial crises happen. If I recall correctly, there was a stock market crash in 2008 that caused a great deal of job loss.

There are shorter cycles of rise and fall within the larger trend. The cycles are relatively consistent, peaking around the start of each year. I assume a lot of that is due to seasonal fluctuations in the job market. A lot of trade industries, especially, only work 9 months per year due to weather; and a lot of people who are otherwise unemployed are able to pick up temporary seasonal work over the holidays, but those retailers, etc. tend to get rid of all of their seasonal help at the new year.

In 2008 we had a major stock market collapse in the United States, which sent us into an economic depression, causing a great deal of job loss and economic uncertainty for a great deal of our population that took years to recover from. The map uses a color coding scheme that relates the geographical regions to the starting digit of the zip code.

Urban Centers: Major cities and metropolitan areas tend to have higher zip code density, with a concentration of colored dots in these regions. This reflects the higher population density and greater demand for postal services in urban centers.

    Coastal Regions: Coastal areas, especially along the California coastline, often exhibit higher zip code density due to both population density and economic activity associated with ports, tourism, and commerce.

    Inland Areas: While zip code density decreases as you move away from major urban centers and coastal regions, there are still pockets of higher density in inland areas, particularly around mid-sized cities and densely populated suburban areas.

    Rural and Remote Areas: Rural and remote regions typically have lower zip code density, with fewer colored dots indicating fewer zip codes. These areas may have larger geographic areas covered by a single zip code due to lower population density and less demand for postal services.

East Coast: The East Coast tends to have a higher density of zip codes compared to the West Coast. This is primarily due to the higher population density and more developed urban areas along the East Coast, such as the Northeast megalopolis stretching from Boston to Washington, D.C.

West Coast: While the West Coast also has densely populated urban areas like Los Angeles, San Francisco, and Seattle, it generally has fewer zip codes compared to the East Coast. This is partly because of the presence of vast uninhabited or sparsely populated areas, such as deserts, mountains, and forests, which may have fewer zip codes covering larger geographic areas.

The main takeaway is that zip code density tends to correlate with population density, economic activity, and geographic features. On the East Coast, where there are densely populated urban areas and established communities, there tends to be a higher density of zip codes to accommodate the higher demand for postal services. In contrast, the West Coast, while also home to major cities, generally has fewer zip codes due to the presence of vast uninhabited or sparsely populated areas.

I've learned that zip code density varies across different regions, with higher density typically found in urban and coastal areas compared to rural and remote regions. Additionally, there is a noticeable difference in zip code density between the East and West coasts of the United States, with the East Coast generally having a higher density of zip codes due to its higher population density and more developed urban areas.
